English sentences are built on a foundation of a subject and a predicate connected by agreement (person and number) and tense. While complex structures exist, the sources emphasize that even the most complicated-looking sentences are essentially simple at their core, adhering to these basic structural requirements.
1. Question Formation
To form a question in English, the tense and agreement markers are typically "extracted" from the verb and moved to the front of the sentence. This often requires the auxiliary word "do" (e.g., does, did) to host these markers when no other auxiliary is present.
•	Two Main Types: 
o	Content Questions: Begin with "wh-words" (what, who, where, etc.) and require specific information as an answer.
o	Yes/No Questions: Begin with tense/agreement markers and can be answered with a simple "yes" or "no".
•	Example: For the sentence "Raju loves pizza," the question form is "Does Raju love pizza?".
2. Question Tags
Question tags are short questions added to the end of declarative sentences to engage the listener, verify information, or seek confirmation.
•	Structural Rules: 
o	An affirmative sentence takes a negative tag; a negative sentence takes an affirmative tag.
o	The tag must use the same tense and subject as the main sentence.
o	Contraction of the tense and negation is mandatory (e.g., "don't you" instead of "do not you").
•	Example: "You speak English, don't you?".
3. Complex and Embedded Sentences
A sentence is considered complex when it contains another sentence (an embedded clause or subordinate clause) within its predicate, usually serving as the object of the verb.
•	Finite vs. Non-finite: 
o	Finite clauses have their own tense (e.g., "I believe [that he is innocent]").
o	Non-finite clauses lack their own tense, often appearing as infinitives (e.g., "I want [to go]").
•	Recursion: This is the capacity to embed a clause within an already embedded clause, a unique property of human language.
•	Example: "I wonder [what her name is]" is a complex sentence because the object of "wonder" is the full sentence "what her name is".
4. Complementizers: That, Whether, and If
Complementizers are functional elements used to introduce embedded clauses.
•	That-Clause: Often introduces a finite sentential object. In many cases, "that" is optional and can be dropped without changing the meaning. 
o	Example: "John knows [that Peter likes Mary]" or "John knows [Peter likes Mary]".
•	Whether and If: These are used to introduce indirect questions, which soften speech and make it less direct and more polite. 
o	Whether is preferred in formal contexts and before to-infinitives or prepositions.
o	If is generally more informal.
o	Example: "I don't know whether she will come".
5. Questions within Complex Sentences
A critical rule for accuracy is that when a question is embedded within a larger sentence, no fronting of tense and agreement occurs in that subordinate clause.
•	Example: It is correct to say, "I asked what you ate," but ungrammatical to say, "I asked what did you eat".

